## Core Principles

- **Clarify Before Coding:** Understand requirements before writing code. Ask questions when intent is unclear. No code without clear goals.
- **Simplicity First:** Choose the simplest viable solution. Complex patterns need explicit justification. Readable code over clever code.
- **Security By Default:** Validate all inputs. No secrets in code. Defense in depth. Least privilege principle.
- **Test-Driven Thinking:** Design all code to be testable from inception. Write tests alongside code. Verify before committing.
</core_principles>

<code_style>
## Code Style

### Naming
- Components/Classes: PascalCase
- Functions/Methods: camelCase with verb prefixes (getUser, calculateTotal)
- Variables: camelCase; booleans use is/has prefix (isLoading, hasError)
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
- Types/Interfaces: PascalCase

### Formatting
- Trailing commas in multi-line structures
- Explicit return types on all functions
- One concept per file; keep files under 300 lines
- Functions under 30 lines; refactor if longer

### Do
- Use strict/explicit types (no `any`; use `unknown` + type guards)
- Prefer composition over inheritance
- Use named constants instead of magic values
- Add JSDoc/TSDoc for public API functions

### Do Not
- No business logic in UI components
- No inline styles (use CSS framework)
- No unhandled promise rejections
- No commented-out code in commits
</code_style>

<security>
## Security Rules

### Input Validation
- Validate ALL user input with schema validation (Zod, Pydantic, etc.)
- Never trust client-side data
- Sanitize HTML before rendering
- Validate file uploads: MIME type, extension, max size

### Injection Prevention
- NEVER concatenate SQL strings -- use parameterized queries only
- NEVER pass user input to shell commands
- NEVER use eval() or Function() with user data
- NEVER use dangerouslySetInnerHTML without sanitization

### Secrets
- No secrets in source code -- environment variables only
- No credentials in client-side code
- Never commit .env files; use .env.example with dummy values
- All AI-generated code requires human security review
</security>

<testing>
## Testing Standards

### Structure
- Arrange-Act-Assert (AAA) pattern for all tests
- One assertion concept per test
- Descriptive names: "should [behavior] when [condition]"

### Coverage Targets
- Critical paths: 80% minimum
- Security code: 90% minimum
- Utilities/helpers: 95% minimum

### Types
- Unit: isolated, fast, no external dependencies
- Integration: component interactions, API endpoints
- E2E: critical user journeys only

### Anti-Patterns to Avoid
- No test interdependencies
- No hardcoded test data (use factories/fixtures)
- No testing implementation details
- Mock external dependencies, not internal logic
</testing>

<workflow>
## Workflow

### Changes
- Atomic: small, self-contained modifications
- Scope: only modify files related to the current task
- No unrelated "improvements" without permission
- Preserve existing code style and formatting

### Commits
- Conventional format: type(scope): description
- Types: feat, fix, docs, style, refactor, test, chore
- Clear, descriptive messages explaining *why* not *what*

### Token Efficiency
- Keep requests focused on specific files or functions
- Avoid regenerating large blocks; prefer targeted edits
- Break large tasks into smaller, sequential steps

### Dependency Governance
- Never add new dependencies without explicit approval or compelling justification

### Industry Standards
- Follow established conventions for the relevant language and tech stack

### Strategic Documentation
- Comment only complex logic or critical functions. Avoid documenting the obvious.

### Self-Review Before Commit
- After generating code, argue against your own solution. Check for redundancy, unnecessary complexity, or simpler alternatives.

### Communication
- Explain reasoning when choosing between conflicting approaches
- Flag security concerns immediately
</workflow>

<uncertainty>
## When Uncertain

- Ask clarifying questions before implementing
- Propose a plan with alternatives and tradeoffs
- Reference existing patterns in the codebase
- Start small, get feedback, then iterate
- Clearly state when a request exceeds available context
</uncertainty>
